{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>This is a family of eukaryotic ribosomal biogenesis regulatory (Rrs1) proteins. Rrs1 was isolated as a factor related to a secretory defect that caused the transcriptional repression of both rRNA and ribosomal protein genes [[cite:PUB00103786]]. This protein is known to localize in the nucleolus where it acts as a ribosome assembly factor. It also localizes at the nuclear periphery where it directly interacts with the membrane-spanning SUN domain protein Mps3 and silent information factor Sir4, both involved in telomere clustering and silencing [[cite:PUB00103789]].</p>\n\n<p>The N-terminal region of Rrs1 plays a role in ribosome biogenesis via interaction with the N-terminal Brix domain of Rpf2. The topology of the Brix domain presents an incomplete duplication of the anticodon-binding domain (ABD) of class IIa aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases. The structure of the Rpf2-Rrs1 complex shows that the N-terminal region of Rrs1 completes the Brix domain of Rpf2 and creates a double anticodon-binding domain [[cite:PUB00103788]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "5wxl", "name" "Crystal structure of the Rrs1 and Rpf2 complex"}, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"pfam" {"PF04939" "Ribosome biogenesis regulatory protein (RRS1)"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Ribosomal biogenesis regulatory protein", "short" "Ribosom_reg"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 40, "domain_architectures" 73, "proteomes" 2391, "taxa" 8294, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 4020, "sets" 0, "proteins" 3983, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 2578}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR007023", :literature {"PUB00103786" {"URL" nil, "issue" "6", "authors" ["Tsuno A" "Miyoshi K" "Tsujii R" "Miyakawa T" "Mizuta K."], "ISO_journal" "Mol Cell Biol", "DOI_URL" nil, "medl